<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-01">
  <title>Early Number Systems and Counting (1.1-1.3)</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Written-number-systems">
    <title>Written Number Systems</title>
    
    <p>
      The earliest evidence of mathematics is a bone found in the village of Ishago in the Democratic Republic on the Congo, which is over 8,000 years old. he markings in the bone are believed to have been tally marks; however, there are patterns in the bone that suggest that more mathematics than just counting is recorded here. For example, one row of the bone contains markings for the prime numbers between 10 and 20. 
    </p>

    <p>
      The Inca built the largest empire in pre-Columbian America. They ruled over a vast landscape that included mountains, deserts, and rain forests. They kept their empire together despite lacking the wheel, pack animals, or writing. Instead of using marking to record numbers, the Inca used knotted strings called Quipu. According to their positions on the string, the knots could signify units, tens, hundreds, thousands, ten thousands or hundred thousands.
    </p>

    <p>
      Written number systems are a culmination of these earlier developments. Tally marks like those on the Ishango bone where first used to record information. Over time more complex recording devices like the quipu were invented. Before the appearance of such devices, there must have been an efficient system of spoken numbers founded on the idea of base to enable numbers to be arranged in efficient groups.
    </p>

    <p>
      In a base system, some number $b$ is selected as the base. Names are assigned to numbers $1, 2, \ldots, b$ and larger numbers are given by combinations of the number names already selected.
    </p>

    <p>
      Many different bases have been used by various cultures throughout history. Here are a several of the more common ones.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Base 2- Used by certain tribes of central Africa
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Base 5- Used by some South American tribes as well as by the Yukaghirs of Siberia.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Base 10- Used in modern mathematics. Also used by Egyptians, Inca, Chinese, Indians, and others.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Base 20- Used by several Native American tribes, most famously the Maya.
          </p>
        </li>
        <p>
          Base 60- Used by ancient Babylonians.
        </p>
      </ul>
    </p>



  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Simple-Grouping-Systems">
    <title>Simple Grouping Systems</title>

    <p>
      There are many types of base systems even among systems sharing the same base. One type is known as a <term>simple grouping system</term>.
    </p>

    <p>
      In a simple grouping system, some number $b$ is selected as a base and symbols are adopted for $1, b, b^2, \ldots$. A number is expressed by using the symbols additively, where each symbol is repeated the required number of times.
    </p>

    <p>
      An example of this type of system is found in the early Egyptian hieroglyphic system. This is a base 10 system.
    </p>

    <p>
      Each picture represents the value of the number. To express multiples of the number you repeat the symbol that many times. For example to express the number <m>300,000</m> you would draw three tadpoles.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Write <m>120,247</m> using Egyptian numerals.
    </p>

    <p>
      Another example of a simple grouping system is Roman numerals. Unlike Egyptian numerals which are multiples of 10, Roman numerals are multiples of 5. In modern use of Roman numerals a smaller numeral before a larger one represents subtraction. For example IV means <m>5-1=4</m>; however, the ancient Romans did not do this.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Write <m>2024</m> using Roman numerals
    </p>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Multiplicative-Grouping-Systems">
    <title>Multiplicative Grouping Systems</title>

    <p>
      In a multiplicative grouping system, after a base $b$ is selected, symbols are chosen for $1, 2, \ldots, b-1$ and a second set of symbols are adopted for $b, b^2, b^3, \ldots$. The symbol of the 2 sets are employed multiplicatively to show how many units of the higher groups are needed.
    </p>

    <p>
      As an example of this let $a = 10$ $b=100$ and $c=1000$. Then we would express the number 7453 as $7c4b5a3$
    </p>

    <p>
      The traditional Chinese numeral system is a multiplicative grouping system with base 10.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Let $a = 10$ $b=100$ and $c=1000$. How would you express the number <m>9268</m> in this system?
    </p>
    
  </subsection>
  
</section>
